'''Yumura-yama''' (湯村山) is a {{ill|mountain|ja|山|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Kofu|ja|甲府市|12=draft}}, {{ill|Yamanashi Prefecture|ja|山梨県|12=draft}}, Japan, at the southern tip of the {{ill|Okuchichibu Mountains|ja|奥秩父山塊|12=draft}}. It has an elevation of 446 meters and is one of the {{ill|Kofu Meizan|ja|甲府名山|12=draft}}.

== Overview ==
Located approximately 1.8 km northwest of {{ill|Kofu Station|ja|甲府駅|12=draft}} on the {{ill|Chuo Main Line|ja|中央本線|12=draft}}, Yumura-yama offers a panoramic view of Kofu City from its summit. The hiking trails are well-maintained, with sections paved with asphalt, making them popular among local residents. From the trailhead near {{ill|Midorigaoka Sports Park|ja|甲府市緑が丘スポーツ公園|12=draft}}, it takes about 20 minutes to reach the junction leading to the Yumura-yama summit and the {{ill|Chiyoda Lake|ja|千代田湖|12=draft}} area. The summit is a further 10 minutes from the junction. Another route starts from Yumura Town.<ref>[https://kofu-tourism.com/course/546 甲府観光ナビ 湯村山をハイキングしよう！]</ref>

== History ==
In 1523 ({{ill|Daiei era|ja|大永|12=draft}} 3), {{ill|Takeda Nobutora|ja|武田信虎|12=draft}} constructed a mountain fortress (Yumura-yama Castle) at the summit. Its location allowed for extensive surveillance and intelligence gathering over the Kofu Basin. Today, remnants such as a well and some minor ruins remain, alongside a reconstructed beacon fire platform ({{ill|Noroshi|ja|狼煙|12=draft}}). The hiking trail also features several {{ill|Cairn tombs|ja|積石塚|12=draft}} along the way.<ref>[https://www.city.kofu.yamanashi.jp/senior/kamejii/064.html 甲府市公式サイト内 湯村山にお城があった！？]</ref>

